metadata.metaValue: These transforms are from the animated controls for the arms/legs. We accumulate them so that we can offset the animation for each robot.

We use a for-each to duplicate the source and add variation, to the starting position of the robot, as well as offset its walking animation.

We animate the robot through motorized constraints.  Rather than apply the animation data directly, we give it to the constraint as a target pose. The constraint tries to achieve this pose through motors with certain physical properties.
The parts of the robot we renamed such that their number in the outliner matches their array index
Since each source instances the same meshes, we can merge them so they all use the same set of shapes.
An example using robots animated procedurally
Important to disable sleep. If the robot comes to rest for too long the motors will not be enough to wake the bodies back up
Set mass based on object size
parts near the ground (ie. the legs) get a boost in mass to aid stability.
Here we prep the mesh's properties. We compute translate using the center of the bounding box, and mass based on its extents.
